<Layout title="🍞 Staton 2025 — Program Logics via Distributive Monoidal Categories">
  <main>

    <a href="/natural-breadcrumbs/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">← back to index</a>

    <h1>Program Logics via Distributive Monoidal Categories</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Bonchi, Di Lavore, Román, Staton · 2025 · <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2507.18238">arXiv:2507.18238</a></p>

    <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-6">No prerequisites. This is the entry point.</p>

    <!-- One sentence -->
    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">Every Hoare rule you learned in your algorithms course — SKIP, COMP, WHILE, ASSIGN — is a <strong>theorem</strong>, not an axiom, once your category has the right structure.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- 1. The Hoare triple -->
    <h3>The Hoare triple</h3>
    <p>You already know this pattern:</p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-4 font-mono text-center">
      <span class="text-gray-400">assert</span> <span class="text-green-300">P</span><span class="text-gray-500">;</span>
      <span class="text-blue-300">run(c)</span><span class="text-gray-500">;</span>
      <span class="text-gray-400">assert</span> <span class="text-green-300">Q</span>
    </div>

    <p>"If P holds before running c, then Q holds after." That's a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hoare_logic">Hoare triple</a>: <code>{'{P}'} c {'{Q}'}</code>. If the precondition doesn't hold, the triple says nothing — it's vacuously satisfied.</p>

    <Repl client:load initialCode={`# {P} c {Q} — if P holds before, Q holds after.

P = lambda x: x > 0
c = lambda x: x * 2
Q = lambda y: y > 0

for x in range(-3, 4):
    if P(x):
        result = c(x)
        assert Q(result), f"Failed: {x} -> {result}"
        print(f"  x={x} -> {result}: Q holds ✓")
    else:
        print(f"  x={x}: P doesn't hold, triple says nothing")
`} />

    <!-- 2. SKIP -->
    <h3>SKIP — doing nothing preserves anything</h3>
    <p>The simplest rule. <code>{'{P}'} skip {'{P}'}</code>. If P is true before doing nothing, P is still true after. Obvious — but it's a theorem, not an assumption.</p>

    <Repl client:load initialCode={`# SKIP: {P} skip {P}
skip = lambda x: x

P = lambda x: x > 0
for x in [1, 5, 100]:
    assert P(skip(x)) == P(x)
    print(f"  skip({x}): P preserved ✓")

print()
print("Nothing happened. That's the point.")
`} />

    <!-- 3. COMP -->
    <h3>COMP — the handshake</h3>
    <p>This is the big one. If <code>{'{P}'} c₁ {'{R}'}</code> and <code>{'{R}'} c₂ {'{Q}'}</code>, then <code>{'{P}'} c₁;c₂ {'{Q}'}</code>.</p>
    <p>R is the <strong>handshake</strong> — stage 1's postcondition is stage 2's precondition. The output guarantee of one stage is the input assumption of the next.</p>

    <!-- SVG diagram: COMP rule -->
    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-6 mb-4 flex justify-center">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 500 160" class="w-full max-w-md" style="font-family: ui-monospace, monospace;">
        <rect x="20" y="50" width="120" height="50" rx="8" fill="#374151" stroke="#6B7280" stroke-width="1.5"/>
        <text x="80" y="80" text-anchor="middle" fill="#86EFAC" font-size="14">stage 1</text>
        <line x1="140" y1="75" x2="180" y2="75" stroke="#6B7280" stroke-width="1.5" marker-end="url(#arrow)"/>
        <rect x="180" y="50" width="120" height="50" rx="8" fill="#1E293B" stroke="#FACC15" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-dasharray="4"/>
        <text x="240" y="73" text-anchor="middle" fill="#FACC15" font-size="12">R</text>
        <text x="240" y="90" text-anchor="middle" fill="#6B7280" font-size="10">handshake</text>
        <line x1="300" y1="75" x2="340" y2="75" stroke="#6B7280" stroke-width="1.5" marker-end="url(#arrow)"/>
        <rect x="340" y="50" width="120" height="50" rx="8" fill="#374151" stroke="#6B7280" stroke-width="1.5"/>
        <text x="400" y="80" text-anchor="middle" fill="#86EFAC" font-size="14">stage 2</text>
        <text x="80" y="35" text-anchor="middle" fill="#9CA3AF" font-size="11">{'{P}'} c₁ {'{R}'}</text>
        <text x="400" y="35" text-anchor="middle" fill="#9CA3AF" font-size="11">{'{R}'} c₂ {'{Q}'}</text>
        <text x="240" y="140" text-anchor="middle" fill="#D1D5DB" font-size="13">Therefore: {'{P}'} c₁;c₂ {'{Q}'}</text>
